        </bioghist>
        <scopecontent id="ref9">
            <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
            <p>Contains her diary, maintained during her fatal pregnancy, in which personal and political concerns are co-mingled; two notebooks with comments on Jews, Zionism, and world affairs; letters from her brother Abram Judah, also a communist who lived in Havana before returning to the USSR, where he died in 1933; letters from her brother Beryl, who came to the U.S. from Ostrolenka in 1935, and letters from her brother Chiel, who remained in Poland. Also contains biographical material (reminiscence, sketch, obituary). Two photographs of Fagel Stern have been transferred to the Library's non-print collection. The diary, notebooks, and most of the letters are in Yiddish, and are arranged alphabetically.</p>
        </scopecontent>
